fields.description:
When pushing over https, users may see an error similar to the following:

{code}
#!bash

The requested URL returned error: 403 while accessing https://{username}@bitbucket.org/{username}/{repo slug}.git/info/refs
fatal: HTTP request failed
{code}

This is a bug. Instead the message should tell users that the account they are trying to push to is over their plan limit.

I have a README.md file that looks like this:

{{{

h1. Installation
# Some step;
# Some step with {{code}} and instructions;
# More {{inline code}} and instructions;\\
}}}

However, items 2 and 3 get cut off at the first backtick, so they appear as:

# Some step with
# More

Listing items from the Issue Tracker using the available issues list macro does not fully support the query syntax. Specifically, the sort order is not honoured.

The following code on the wiki will list the issues in order of most recently modified instead of by priority (greatest to least):\\
{{{\\
<<issues ?status=open&status=new&sort=-priority list>>\\
}}}

This workds just fine:

{{{\\
curl -k --user myUsername:myPassword https://api.bitbucket.org/1.0/user/repositories/?format=xml\\
}}}

Same user/pass and uri from .NET fails:

{{{\\
WebRequest request = WebRequest.Create("https://api.bitbucket.org/1.0/user/repositories/?format=xml");\\
request.Credentials = new NetworkCredential("myUsername", "myPassword");\\
WebResponse response = request.GetResponse();\\
}}}

WebException: The remote server returned an error: (401) Unauthorized.

I receive the following error when uploading from my custom domain, but it works OK from bitbucket.org.\\
{{{\\
<Error><Code>AccessDenied</Code><Message>Invalid according to Policy: Policy Condition failed: ["eq", "$success_action_redirect", "http://code.accursoft.com/accursoft/time-light/downloads/add"]</Message><RequestId>605205BA1E64DC52</RequestId><HostId>rfKT0DFMCojJwq+1IcFitDzHaEsWVhQ1NM2jqz0Xf12yi3JrEjl0d7KLe2jQJTna</HostId></Error>\\
}}}
